Adopt Jack!🐶

Jack is a family dog through-and-through. This one year old husky wants to be friends with everyone; he likes meeting new people, loves kids, and great with other dogs - he even likes cats. Jack is house and crate trained and ready to share all of his love and happiness with his forever family! 

Jack is pretty much a Labrador Retriever in a Husky body. He is a happy guy who wants to have fun with his people. Jack is energetic and needs mental stimulation, but he is also just a goofy love bug who wants to hang out with his person. Jack’s ideal family will be active and excited to bring Jack exploring with them - we know he will be an excellent adventure buddy to the people lucky enough to bring him home!🐾

Huge thanks to @jamesmaslow for finding the time to meet Jack and helping him find his forever home. It takes a village.🙏🏼

If you are interested in adopting Jack, please fill out an app via the linktree in our bio or email adopt@iswmp.org.

Coffee, ice baths and daily fitness…but not always in that order. It’s hard to maintain some of my routine on tour but daily fitness (and coffee let’s be real) is a non negotiable. What are your must-do daily habits? Drop me a comment!

I used to do 100 push-ups a day and now I’ve upped that to 200! Once that gets easy I’ll increase it to 300 and so on. Building daily habits is one of my keys to success. If you don’t have a daily routine, start one now! Pick one healthy habit and do it at the same time every day, then add a new one one next week or next month. Pretty soon you’ll have a badass daily routine! Comment below one of your favorite daily routines ⬇️

I met a survivor from the Nova music festival which took place near the Gaza border. Yonatan along with thousands of others gathered here to celebrate love and peace. He described the moments the music turned to chaos as Hamas terrorists infiltrated with rocket fire and machine guns.
Yonatan wrote a song about his experience. 

He sings about the whistling bullets and falling children from his memories in this very field, but he also sings of the sense of growing hope around him as Israelis come together to help one another and fight for their right to exist.

As a mucisian who has played so many concerts just like this…I simply cannot imagine this happening to me or my fans. But it could.
A terrible surprise…

Yeela and her brother, Evyatar, grew up watching Big Time Rush. The joy of watching our show and listening to our music is something they shared together. 

Evyatar went to a music festival on October 7th. Now he is being held hostage in Gaza.

I can’t even begin to imagine what his sister and all of these hundreds of families are going through. 

Over the next few days, Israel negotiated for many of the children to be released, but it’s not over until every last hostage, including Evyatar, is returned home. They did nothing to deserve this.

Jamal is a Muslim Zaka volunteer and was one of the first responders of October 7th, responsible for collecting the bodies of the victims. 

“I’m supposed to be used to these horrors, but what happened here... it was like nothing I’ve ever seen.”

He described the state they found the bodies in, the wreckage from Palestinian civilians that joined in the looting and killing, and how still, 47 days later, he can barely sleep at night from the nightmares.

He found murdered Muslims and Jews alike, Hamas did not differentiate. As a Muslim Arab, he wants it to be clear, “This has nothing to do with our religion. Our religion is about peace.”
Happy Thanksgiving and Shabbat Shalom from Israel!

This is the point on the Gaza border where terrorists infiltrated to massacre the peaceful village of Kfar Aza. 

I can’t comprehend what could drive people to such violent hate, much like we saw on 9/11. 

I spoke with Grisha Yakubovich, the former mayor of Gaza, to discuss the war on values that we see here: How Israel, just like the US, values life above all. Hamas values death, as they put it, “we are called a nation of martyrs, and are proud to sacrifice martyrs.”

This is the result of the extremist Hamas-ISIS ideology, and we, representatives of the free world, have a responsibility to stand against terror.

“Never again” - I’ve heard those words a thousand times.

As the Jewish people face the worst atrocity since the Holocaust, it’s critical to stand up and fight against antisemitism, misinformation, and the terror organizations including Hamas determined to eliminate the Jewish state and people.

Thank you, Idan, for this important conversation. 

#neveragainisnow

Like a lot of you, I love to travel, hang out with friends and go to music festivals…just like Hersh Goldberg-Polin.

Hersh, an American-Israeli young man, went to celebrate his holiday at Nova this year, an all-night festival about peace, love, and music. Now, he is held hostage in Gaza.

There are hostages from over 30 countries, representing 5 religions and all ages. This isn’t an Israeli-Palestinian crisis. It is an international one.

In the heartbreaking conversation I had with Hersh’s parents, Rachel and Jon, their determination in face of devastation moved me. They said, “even if Hersh walks through the door tomorrow, we’ll keep fighting. We will not stop until every last hostage is brought home.”

Their fight is our fight too. We need to bring them home.

#bringthemhome

This tattoo melds the stark reality of a skull with the dynamic presence of a butterfly to convey a message of life’s resilience and continuity. The skull, a representation of life’s inevitable conclusion, contrasts with the butterfly, traditionally seen as a symbol of change and endurance, embodying the human spirit’s ability to adapt and survive. As the butterfly confronts its reflection on the skull, it prompts a reflection on our own journey through life’s challenges, underscoring the strength and tenacity inherent in our nature. This design is a bold testament to the unyielding cycle of existence. @jamesmaslow explained AND I Executed 💀🦋
